    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Ah, I see where the confusion lies. Let me clear the mist with a more straightforward explanation, devoid of goblin lore. In the world of real estate transactions, the escrow account is a secure account managed by a neutral third party, often a law firm or a title company, not an individual. This account holds the money you pay for the house, ensuring that the funds are available to pay the seller and cover any other agreed-upon expenses, such as closing costs, taxes, and any repairs needed before the sale is finalized.\n\nOnce you sign the purchase agreement and deposit your earnest money into the escrow account, the funds are held securely until the closing date. At that time, the escrow company will distribute the money to the seller, pay off any liens or mortgages on the property, and ensure that the title is transferred to you. The bank or financial institution that holds the escrow account is responsible for managing these funds according to the instructions provided by the escrow company and the terms of the real estate contract.\n\nSo, in essence, the escrow account is a financial safeguard for both you and the seller, ensuring that the transaction proceeds smoothly and that all parties fulfill their obligations before the property changes hands. It's a bit like having a trusted goblin",
      "source": "target",
